<HEADLINE>
<P>
FISHERMEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * As an individual many years retired from hunting and fishing, I keep 
wondering from the daily news why hunters as a group are so much smarter and 
more intelligent than fisherman as a group. Hunters learned a 100 years ago 
when they reduced the plentiful beaver and buffalo almost to extinction and did 
kill off the last of our many billions of passenger pigeons that men just 
cannot go out and slaughter every wild thing in sight or reach with no thought 
of the future. 
</P>
<P>
 Over much of the world varieties of fish, once diet staples, have disappeared 
from the waters by as much as 90%. Fisherman still do not get the idea that 
fish as a resource is finite. Fishermen, the professional ones, have to go 
farther and work harder. Fish prices go up while boat owners cry the blues. 
Greed still dominates and seemingly will until all sources of fish, even the 
least desirable, are exhausted. The handwriting is on the wall for all to see, 
if they can only read. 
</P>
<P>
 JOHN D. ANDREWS 
</P>
<P>
 Palos Verdes Peninsula 
</P>
</TEXT>
