<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEST SCORES NO TRUE MEASURE OF SUCCESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Who and what are served by comparing California Learning Assessment Standards 
test scores? 
</P>
<P>
 Scores are predictable. High numbers of English as a second language students, 
transient populations, and cultures that do not give a high priority to 
education, always score lower. Schools do not get to pick the students they 
serve. 
</P>
<P>
 Low test scores inaccurately reflect the quality of the schools and teachers. 
When will a test score indicate success rather than failure? Taking an 
immigrant and teaching him or her to read and write in English -- even at a 
beginning level -- is a success. 
</P>
<P>
 ADRIENNE MACK, Shadow Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
