<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHUTTLE ASTRONAUTS READY ENDEAVOUR FOR LANDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The space shuttle Endeavour's astronauts test-fired their steering jets and 
wiggled their flaps Sunday in preparation for their return home. 
</P>
<P>
 Endeavour is scheduled to land just before 9 a.m. PDT Tuesday, ending an Earth 
observation mission that began April 9.Weather forecasts are favorable for a 
landing at the Kennedy Space Center. 
</P>
<P>
 Commander Sidney Gutierrez and pilot Kevin Chilton activated hydraulic systems 
that drive wing and tail flaps Sunday and then fired 44 steering jets on the 
shuttle's nose and tail. Mission Control said the checkout went well. 
</P>
<P>
 The $366-million radar imaging system in Endeavour's cargo bay continued to 
scan Earth. 
</P>
<P>
 NASA officials said the radar system has filled 124 reels of tape on board the 
shuttle with recorded data for later analysis on Earth. Some pictures are also 
transmitted to the ground. Scientists at the Johnson Space Center in Houston 
said they were delighted with the images they were getting. 
</P>
<P>
 At a crew news conference televised to reporters at Mission Control, the 
astronauts talked about the spectacular views. 
</P>
