<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHAMBER IN TUSTIN ELECTS NEW OFFICERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A local lawyer was elected president of the Tustin Chamber of Commerce last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
 Vic Gorham, 64, will also serve as head of the executive committee, the 
chamber's policy-making body.His one-year term will begin July 1. 
</P>
<P>
 Cliff Polston of the Tustin Boys and Girls Club was elected vice president, Al 
Shifberg-Mencher of Shifberg-Mencher Associates, was chosen as chief financial 
officer, and Jim Kane of Saddleback Chapel was elected secretary. 
</P>
<P>
 The executive committee includes Paul Irby, the outgoing president. 
</P>
<P>
 Gorham, who moved his law practice from Irvine in 1984, said that the Chamber 
of Commerce must help retain businesses in the city by improving further an 
already "fine business climate." 
</P>
<P>
 One example is the business expo that the Chamber of Commerce is sponsoring 
April 28 at the Tustin Boys and Girls Club, in which local businesses can 
display their products and services, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Gorham said he thinks the local economy is slowly coming out of a recession. 
</P>
<P>
 Executive Director Thomas P. Brennan said three directors also were appointed 
to one-year terms on the board. They were Jerry Adams of I.D. Investments, Lou 
Bone of X.L. Lock Inc. and Asta Gasper of Home Savings of America. 
</P>
<P>
 Brennan said nine of the 13 members of the board are elected to three-year 
terms and three are appointed to one-year terms. The outgoing president 
completes the board membership. 
</P>
<P>
 The new officers will be installed June 25 at the Revere House Restaurant in 
Tustin. 
</P>
