<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; COUNCIL TO CONSIDER OPTIONS ON GARBAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A month after a countywide trash panel decided to scuttle plans for a regional 
waste authority, the Simi Valley City Council tonight will consider other 
options for controlling the city's trash flow. 
</P>
<P>
 The council will also discuss asking the county to refund $22,600 that the 
city paid toward an audit of existing countywide trash agencies as part of an 
effort to form the new authority. 
</P>
<P>
 Similar fees were paid by the county and its other nine cities before the 
Ventura County Waste Commission in March agreed to abandon plans to form a 
countywide waste authority. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Bill Davis said that he was glad that plans for the authority 
collapsed and that he hopes that the city can recover its share of the audit 
fee. 
</P>
<P>
 "The differences in trash philosophy just run too deep for all of us to get 
together as a single agency," he said. "Letting us go our own separate way is a 
much more viable approach." 
</P>
<P>
 The city had planned to add a five-cent-a-month surcharge to residents' trash 
bills to cover the cost of the audit. SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
